Type narrowing is TypeScript's ability to REFINE the type of a variable inside a conditional block based on checks you write:

```typescript
function process(value: string | number) {
  if (typeof value === 'string') {
    value.toUpperCase(); // TypeScript knows value is string here
  } else {
    value.toFixed(2); // TypeScript knows value is number here
  }
}
```

TypeScript's control flow analysis tracks what each guard proves and adjusts the type accordingly. The narrowing happens in the TYPE SYSTEM — no extra runtime code is generated beyond your existing checks.

A DISCRIMINATED UNION (also called tagged union or algebraic data type) has members that each share a common literal field — the DISCRIMINANT:

```typescript
type Result =
  | { status: 'ok'; data: string }
  | { status: 'error'; message: string }
  | { status: 'loading' };

function handle(r: Result) {
  switch (r.status) {
    case 'ok': return r.data.toUpperCase();
    case 'error': return r.message;
    case 'loading': return 'Loading...';
    // TypeScript will warn if you add a new status and forget to handle it
  }
}
```

Benefits:
1. TypeScript cannot narrow without a discriminant — adding `status: 'pending'` without a case causes a compile error.
2. Models real-world state machines (loading/error/success) safely.
3. No runtime overhead — just switch on the tag.

A TYPE PREDICATE is a function with return type `arg is T`:

```typescript
function isString(x: unknown): x is string {
  return typeof x === 'string';
}

const value: unknown = 'hello';
if (isString(value)) {
  value.toUpperCase(); // TypeScript knows value is string here
}
```

Without a type predicate, a function returning `boolean` doesn't tell TypeScript anything about types. With the `x is T` annotation, calling the function in an `if` condition narrows the type.

When to use:
• When the narrowing logic is complex and you want to reuse it
• When encapsulating `instanceof` or multiple checks
• For array filtering: `items.filter((x): x is string => typeof x === 'string')` gives `string[]` not `(string|null)[]`

The EXHAUSTIVENESS CHECK pattern:

```typescript
type Shape = { kind: 'circle'; r: number } | { kind: 'square'; side: number };

function area(s: Shape): number {
  switch (s.kind) {
    case 'circle': return Math.PI * s.r ** 2;
    case 'square': return s.side ** 2;
    default:
      const _exhaustive: never = s; // ERROR if any union member unhandled
      throw new Error(`Unhandled: ${_exhaustive}`);
  }
}
```

If you add `| { kind: 'triangle'; base: number; height: number }` to `Shape` and forget to add a case, `s` in the `default` branch is `{ kind: 'triangle'; ... }` — NOT `never` — so assigning it to `never` produces a compile error.

Alternatively, use a helper: `function assertNever(x: never): never { throw new Error(); }`

Both are JavaScript runtime operators that TypeScript understands for narrowing:

`typeof` — checks PRIMITIVE types:
```typescript
if (typeof x === 'string') { /* x: string */ }
if (typeof x === 'number') { /* x: number */ }
// Valid: string, number, boolean, bigint, symbol, function, object, undefined
```

`instanceof` — checks CLASS/CONSTRUCTOR identity via the prototype chain:
```typescript
if (x instanceof Date) { /* x: Date */ }
if (x instanceof Error) { /* x: Error */ }
```

Limitations:
• `typeof null === 'object'` — a famous JS bug, use separate null check
• `instanceof` only works with classes, not plain object types or interfaces
• `instanceof` can fail across iframes (different realm = different constructors)

The `in` operator checks if a property exists on an object. TypeScript uses this to narrow union types:

```typescript
type Cat = { meow(): void };
type Dog = { bark(): void };

function speak(animal: Cat | Dog) {
  if ('meow' in animal) {
    animal.meow(); // TypeScript knows it's Cat
  } else {
    animal.bark(); // TypeScript knows it's Dog
  }
}
```

This works because TypeScript can infer which union members have the given property key. This is the standard way to narrow unions of unrelated object types that don't share a common discriminant.

ASSERTION FUNCTIONS use the `asserts` keyword in the return type:

```typescript
function assert(cond: boolean, msg: string): asserts cond {
  if (!cond) throw new Error(msg);
}

function assertIsString(x: unknown): asserts x is string {
  if (typeof x !== 'string') throw new Error('Not a string!');
}
```

Difference from type predicates:
• Type predicates narrow INSIDE the `if` block when the function returns `true`.
• Assertion functions narrow FOR THE REST OF THE CURRENT SCOPE — they either throw or let execution continue, and TypeScript assumes the condition holds from that point forward.

```typescript
const value: unknown = fetch();
assertIsString(value);
value.toUpperCase(); // TypeScript knows value is string here — no if needed
```
